"On the very first day the directors realised that one of their chief problems would be how to cope with the homeward rush when the day’s work was done, for the crush round the approaches at Farringdon Street was compared to the crush at the pit-door of a popular theatre. More than 30,000 people were carried that day, and the traffic for the first three weeks gave an average of 29,196 a day, with receipts of £346 7s. 6d. The directors, therefore, striking while the iron was hot, lost no time in appealing for fresh capital in order to push on with the extensions which they had in mind, and, feeling secure, as they had every right to do, of the appreciation of the"